    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pure vector (semantic) search retrieves documents that are conceptually similar to the query, even when no exact words match. Pure keyword (BM25) search retrieves documents that contain the exact terms in the query, even when the meaning is different. Neither is universally better. Hybrid search runs both in parallel and fuses the ranked results, combining the recall advantages of semantic search with the precision advantages of keyword matching. This document covers how to implement hybrid search from scratch in PostgreSQL and with Weaviate, and how to tune the fusion weight for your retrieval task."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Flowchart of hybrid search: a user query splits into BM25 keyword search (tokenise, IDF weight, exact term match) and vector semantic search (embed, cosine similarity). BM25 returns doc3:0.82, doc1:0.71, doc7:0.54. Vector returns doc1:0.91, doc5:0.78, doc3:0.62. Both sets flow into score fusion (RRF or linear alpha weighting) which produces re-ranked results passed to Claude's context window."
        }
      },
